# Production Readiness Gate — Namibia Sports Platform

## RULE 1: No In-Memory State for Persistent Data
- Use Supabase/Drizzle for any data that must survive function invocations
- Session management must use Supabase Auth
- Netlify Functions are stateless — no module-level caches without TTL

## RULE 2: No Synchronous Long-Running Operations in Handlers
- tRPC procedures must return quickly; offload heavy work to background jobs
- Use Supabase Edge Functions or queued workflows for file processing, emails
- External API calls: set explicit timeouts (e.g. AbortSignal.timeout(5000))

## RULE 3: Every External Call: Error Handling, Retry, Timeout
- All fetch/axios/Supabase calls must have try/catch
- Include retry logic for transient failures (429, 503)
- Timeout configuration required

## RULE 4: Rate Limiting on Public Endpoints
- Auth endpoints: 5 attempts/minute per IP
- General tRPC procedures: consider rate limiting for public mutations
- Webhook endpoints: verify signatures before processing

## RULE 5: Database Queries Must Be Bounded
- Every list query MUST have .limit() or .range() — default 25, max 100
- Use cursor-based pagination for large datasets
- No N+1 patterns

## RULE 6: Connection Pooling
- Use Drizzle with postgres-js; configure for serverless
- Supabase connection pooler (port 6543) for serverless
- Singleton DB client at module level

## RULE 7: Environment-Specific Configuration Explicit
- All env vars in .env, referenced via process.env
- .env.example must document every required variable
- Fail fast at startup if required vars missing

## RULE 8: Error Boundaries and Graceful Degradation
- React components: ErrorBoundary at page level
- tRPC: structured error responses, never expose raw errors to client
- Fallback UI for data-dependent components

## RULE 9: Real-Time Must Handle Disconnection
- Supabase Realtime: handle CHANNEL_ERROR, TIMED_OUT
- Reconnection logic with exponential backoff
- Show connection status to users

## RULE 10: Pre-Deploy Scale Sanity Check
Document in PR: expected concurrent users, DB tables that grow, external API limits, cost at 10x scale.
